  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Proof of Proposition 6.2.",
    "Similar to the proof of Proposition 14 in Acemoglu, Huttenlocher, Ozdaglar, and Siderius (2024), the maximal revenue the platform can collect from the firms (and specifically from the naïfs) is given by m * (α (L), α (R)) ≤ L λ (α (L) + α (R)) for some constant L λ > 0.",
    "The total advertising revenue is thus bounded above (1 -λ)L λ (α (L) + α (R)), but the loss in subscription revenue from the platform from advertising is (α (L) + α (R))T.",
    "For λ = 1 -T /L λ, if λ ′ > λ, then the platform opts for a fully subscription-based business model instead, with the sophisticated users protecting the naïve ones from an ad-based plan that fails to generate sufficient revenue to compensate for the loss in subscription.",
    "This leads posterior beliefs to equal H = H ≺ H, which by Lemma 1(ii) moderates the positions of the political parties (undoing the effect identified in Proposition 5.2(ii))."
  ],
